You **can‚Äôt install Terraform itself with pip**, because Terraform is **not a Python package**‚Äîit‚Äôs a standalone HashiCorp binary.  
But you *can* install it **via Pipenv** using a Python wrapper package that bundles the Terraform binary.

The correct way is to use either:

*   **terraform-bin** (GitHub wrapper) [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/karstenjakobsen/terraform-bin)
*   **terraform-binary / terraform-executor** (PyPI wrapper) [\[pypi.org\]](https://pypi.org/project/terraform-executor/)

Both packages download and manage the Terraform binary for you inside your Pipenv environment.

***

# ‚úÖ Install Terraform using Pipenv (Recommended Method)

### **1. Create / enter a Pipenv environment**

```bash
pipenv shell
```

### **2. Install the Terraform wrapper**

You have two good options:

### **Option A ‚Äî terraform-bin**

```bash
pipenv install terraform-bin
```

After installation you can run:

```bash
terraform init
```

 [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/karstenjakobsen/terraform-bin)

***

### **Option B ‚Äî terraform-executor / terraform-binary (PyPI)**

```bash
pipenv install terraform-executor   -------------- insttaled using this command in past
```

Then use Terraform normally:

```bash
terraform init
```

 [\[pypi.org\]](https://pypi.org/project/terraform-executor/)

***

# üîç Why this works

These packages **bundle the actual Terraform binary** and expose it through your Pipenv environment, so you avoid manually downloading and placing binaries in PATH.

***

# üëç Which should you choose?

*   **terraform-bin** ‚Üí Actively maintained wrapper on GitHub
*   **terraform-executor / terraform-binary** ‚Üí Published on PyPI

Both work similarly.

